results.title: A Lifesaving Transplant for Coral Reefs
results.abstract: A quick-grow laboratory technique, called microfragmenting, may make it possible to mass-produce reef-building corals for transplanting onto dead or dying reefs that took centuries to develop.

media.caption: A mountainous star coral colony that was grown from an inch-square fragment cut a year earlier off of a parent colony.
Divers "plant" live coral fragments that were grown in a nursery onto dead coral skeletons in the Florida keys using epoxy putty.
David Vaughan with one of nine shallow 180-gallon salt water tanks, which contain colonies of massive corals grown from tiny coral fragments.
